pgTitle: List of women in the Heritage Floor

rows.text: Poet, intellectual and founder of the Bolivian feminist movement.
Philanthropist, politician, poet, was an Orthodox Christian who fought for the protection of Jews and pagans
Poet and physician, rejected marriage as it was a hindrance to her career. Wrote books about gynecology and obstetrics.
Queen of Wessex alongside husband King Ine of Wessex. Fought battles alongside Ine. In 728 they relinquished the crown to her brother and lived amongst the poor in Rome.
Rejected the advances of Roman military officials and was tortured by having her breasts cut off,

Abbess of St. Mary's in Quedlinburg, where fine needlework and weavings were created, as well as manuscript illustrations. Agnes encouraged artistic creation and supported a healthy art industry with her nuns' creations.
She was the first woman executed for witchcraft in England.

The first female gynecologist. She disguised herself as a man in order to go to medical school. She became a gynecologist, and when male doctors realized women preferred her services, they charged her with malpractice. She outed herself, and they tried to pass a law prohibiting women to practice medicine. The law was eventually changed, due to women speaking out, until the 12th century AD.
Julia Agrippina, Roman noble women, the wife of the emperor Claudius and mother of Nero, who effectively ruled the empire for two decades through her influence over both her husband and son.
She was called the Witch of Kilkenny, and was one of the earliest women in Ireland to be accused of witchcraft. All of her husbands died during marriage,

As an elderly woman, she was accused of being a witch by the children of her employer. Her trial was held in 1593, and she was hung, along with two relatives, as the results of the children's testimony.
The first female physician from Bolivia.
American pianist and first female composer in the United States.
Virgin goddess of fertility, love and war.
She was arrested and prosecuted in the last wave of Christian persecutions, dying in 304. She was sainted in the 5th century.
The correct spelling of her name is Anaxandra. She was a painter.
Teacher, poet, labor organizer and feminist who co-published La Mujer Moderna (English: The Modern Woman), with her sister.

A noblewoman, she was accused of witchcraft and under torture she confessed. She was convicted and burned alive. The city of Toulouse has no records of her trial and historians question the validity of the story.
Schwägel or Schwegelin was an alleged German (Bavarian) witch, who was long considered the last person to be executed for witchcraft in Germany. It is now believed she died forgotten in prison.
American politician, pamphleteer and lobbyist who served as an advisor to Abraham Lincoln.
inventor of woven cloth and net making
Helped Theseus overthrow Minos and married him.
Main deity, queen of Hatti, Heaven and earth. Also known as Arinna.
agricultural deity, moon goddess, watcher of forests... many meanings in many cultures
virgin goddess, warrior and patron of culture, deity of artists and architects, weavers, protector of Athens
Pioneer of women's education. Founded the first girls' schools in Bulgaria.
Excelled at multiple sports in the early-to-mid twentieth century. Olympic gold medalist; in the top ten of multiple "Greatest Athlete" lists.
Co-ruled w/husband city of Lagash, early philanthropist
Produced the first translations of Roman Classical literature into Danish.
Moon goddess, huntress, ruler of women's societies
Also called Wadjet. The patron and protector of Lower Egypt.
hunter, warrior, Diana avenged her death
Apollo fell in love with her, among other tales
Odyssey, turned men into swine, lived alone on her island
Sister of Helen of Troy, killed family
Carried off to Crete by Zeus, married King of Crete, Minos.
Leader of women's expedition against Babylon
Goddess of turning wheel, divination, fertility
Goddess of marriage, love and home
goddess of the moon and underworld
Husband's attempts to lure her back started Trojan War
chief feminine deity, married to Zeus
Educator and feminist, founded the first secondary school for girls in Hungary
Hero of the Rape of the Sabine Women
General of army of Mysian women who fought in Trojan War
Co-ruler with sisters of Amazon capital of Themiscyra

Swiss scholar who had extensive knowledge of many subjects, including theology and medicine. Known for her writings on the status of women and is regarded as a precursor by the Swiss women's movement.
Mother of Heaven/Queen of all Gods
One of first female musicians recorded in history
former innkeeper and beer seller, came to throne, founded 3rd dynasty, queen
Daughters of Mars with sister, Amazon queens
Killed herself after being raped due to fear of being accused as an adulteress
Saint Matilda, Duchess Consort of Saxony and German Queen, founded several convents and a canonry
Led 30,000 Libyan women to battle against Gorgons, another Amazon tribe
Could be Naqi'a-Zakutu, Assyrian queen c. 704-626
Wove the world on her loom, virgin goddess
Helped create humans out of clay
healing deity, cured Enkin's rib, related to myth of Adam's rib
Queen, wife of Sesostris II, "ruler of all women", progressive leader of Egyptian women's rights
Creator of spirit of human life
co-ruled with sisters Antiope and Hippolyte
an Egyptian priestess-musician who served the creator god Ptah, the god of fire, in the temple of Memphis Ancient Egypt. Some sources ascribe to her the true authorship of the Iliad and the Odyssey.
Persephone, raped by Zeus, many stories
Leader of group of cross dressing women in play by Aristophanes
Consulted by psychics in temple named after her
Female serpent lived near temple of Delphi
priestess, mother of Romulus and Remus
Queen, one of two women to lead Babylon
Goddess of heaven and the moon. Also spelled Tanit.
A Greek priestess, she was a tutor of the philosopher and mathematician Pythagoras.
Theodora was the wife of Byzantine emperor Theophilus (ruled 829–842). She was canonized after her death for reversing the policy of Iconoclasm (prohibition on the worship of icons).
A mystic and a major figure in the Catholic Church, she is credited as a leader of the Counter Reformation and with reviving religious spirit in Spain .
Legal scholar and author of books on grammar.

Tituba was a 17th-century Carib Indian slave from Barbados or Guiana, belonging to Samuel Parris of Salem, Massachusetts. Tituba was one of the first three people accused of practicing witchcraft during the Salem witch trials which took place in 1692. Tituba confessed and implicated other women in the colony in order to save herself from execution. She was later sold by Parris and relocated outside of Salem.
A half human, half donkey, daemon of the Etruscan underworld. She had a vulture's beak, wings, and hair made of serpents.
An upper-class courtesan, author and philosopher, she published a Neoplatonic essay on the nature of love in which she insists on women's autonomy in romantic relationships.
An English woman accused of causing the death of three people and hung for witchcraft.

Russian revolutionary and narodnik born in Kazan. She was leader of Narodnaya Volya (the People's Will), a revolutionary socialist organization which aimed to depose the state regime through terrorism and was involved in the planning of several terrorist acts, including the assassination of Czar Alexander II in 1881.

Russian Marxist writer and revolutionary. In 1883, she helped found the Liberation of Labor, the first Russian Marxist group. Later, she served on the editorial board of Iskra, a revolutionary Marxist newspaper. After the Russian Social Democratic Party split in 1903, Zasulich became a leader of the Menshevik faction.
Italian poet, stateswoman and political leader. Married to the lord of Correggio, after his death in 1518 she took charge of the state as well as the education of her two children.
The virgin goddess of the hearth, home, and family in Roman religion.

American leader of the woman's suffrage movement. She was a radical who advocated the eight-hour day, a progressive income tax, profit sharing, and social welfare programs. In 1872, she ran for president of the United States.

A pioneering Australian feminist politician who campaigned for women's suffrage and social reform. She stood for parliament five times, was a vocal opponent of capitalism and the White Australia policy, and a staunch pacifist, campaigning for peace during World WarI.
Identified in the New Testament and in the Quran as the mother of Jesus who conceived through divine intervention. Revered for centuries as the feminine aspect of the divine.
Author, poet and gardener whose successful 50-year bisexual open marriage scandalised society.
Italian noblewoman and poet, considered the most influential woman of the Italian Renaissance and friend and muse to Michelangelo.
Musical prodigy who's harpsichordist performances, teaching, recordings and writings played a large role in reviving the popularity of the harpsichord in the early 20th century.
Native American noblewoman whose life was recorded in the 1653 children's historical novel The Royal Diaries'
American author who famous for her novels of frontier life on the Great Plains.
A woman seer who called up the ghost of the recently deceased prophet Samuel, at the demand of King Saul.
Russian socialist revolutionary nicknamed The "Babushka" (Little Grandmother) of the Russian Revolution.
Slavic goddess of life, love, and fertility. Commonly spelled Živa.
